## How to Create Design System Components

The design system starts empty. When a designer asks for components -- either by describing them, sharing screenshots, or asking for specific UI patterns -- follow these steps.

### Creating a component

**In the core repo** (developing the tool):

1. **Add CSS classes** to `public/styles/ds.css`. Use design tokens from `shared.css` (colors, radii, fonts, spacing). Follow the naming convention: `.ds-<component>` for the main class, `.ds-<component>-<part>` for sub-elements.
2. **Create a preview HTML file** at `public/data/design-system/components/<name>.html`. This is a pure HTML fragment -- no `<!doctype>`, no `<html>`, no `<head>`, no `<body>`, no style imports. The design system page injects it into a container that already has `shared.css` and `ds.css` loaded.
3. **Register it** in `public/data/design-system/registry.json` -- add it to an existing group/category or create new ones.

**In a company repo** (using the tool):

1. **Create a preview HTML file** at `public/data/design-system/components/<company-slug>/<name>.html`. Same format -- pure HTML fragment. Use inline styles or classes from `company.css` for company-specific styling.
2. **Register it** in `public/data/design-system/registry.json` with `"file": "<company-slug>/<name>.html"`.
3. **If you need new CSS classes**, add them to `public/data/design-system/company.css` (not `ds.css`). Prefix with the company slug (e.g. `.jh-card`). Or use inline styles in the preview HTML -- that's fine for simple components.

### Preview HTML file format

- Pure HTML fragment (no document structure tags)
- Can use inline styles for layout within the preview (e.g. wrapping in a flex container)
- Must use CSS classes from `ds.css` and tokens from `shared.css`
- Keep it minimal -- just enough to show the component in context
- Example for a button preview:
  ```html
  <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 12px;">
    <button class="btn btn-primary">Primary</button>
    <button class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">Primary Small</button>
  </div>
  ```

### Registry structure

The `registry.json` file controls the design system page layout:

```json
{
  "groups": [
    { "id": "foundations", "name": "Foundations" },
    { "id": "inputs", "name": "Inputs & Controls" }
  ],
  "categories": [
    {
      "group": "foundations",
      "name": "Colors",
      "layout": "row",
      "components": [
        { "id": "colors-bg", "file": "colors-bg.html", "label": "Backgrounds" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

- **Groups** are top-level sections that stack vertically. Each gets a header row.
- **Categories** belong to a group and appear as horizontal cards under that group.
- Each category has a `components` array -- each component gets its own preview file.
- Use `"layout": "row"` on a category to lay out its components side-by-side (good for color swatches, button variants, icon sets).
- Group IDs should be lowercase, hyphenated (e.g. `cards-content`, `inputs-controls`).

### User content separation

All user-created content in a company repo must stay cleanly separated from tool files. The rule is simple: **everything the team creates goes under `public/data/`**. Never edit tool-level files (`shared.css`, `ds.css`, `scripts/`, root HTML pages, etc.).

#### Design system components: use a company subfolder

Put components in `public/data/design-system/components/<company-slug>/`, not directly in `components/`. The company slug comes from the repo name (e.g. `design-core-acme` → `acme`).

- **Path**: `public/data/design-system/components/<company-slug>/<component>.html` (e.g. `components/acme/card-payment.html`)
- **Registry**: Set `file` to include the subfolder: `"file": "acme/card-payment.html"`

This avoids merge conflicts when pulling upstream and makes it obvious which components belong to the team.

#### Brand overrides: use `company.css`

**Never edit `shared.css` or `ds.css` in a company repo.** Those are tool files that update via upstream pulls.

Instead, create `public/data/design-system/company.css` for brand-specific overrides. The design system page (and prototypes) auto-load this file if it exists. It loads after `shared.css` and `ds.css`, so overrides take effect via CSS specificity.

Use it for:

- **Colors**: Override `--bg-0`, `--bg-1`, `--neon-blue`, `--neon-blue-rgb`, `--neon-teal`, `--neon-teal-rgb`, `--text`, `--muted`, `--muted-2`, or add new brand tokens
- **Typography**: Override `--font-body`, `--font-display`, add `@import` for Google Fonts
- **Shape**: Override `--radius-sm`, `--radius-md`, `--radius-lg`, `--radius-xl`, `--shadow`, `--shadow-soft`
- **New component classes**: Add company-specific CSS classes (prefix with your company slug, e.g. `.jh-card`)

Example `company.css`:
```css
@import url("https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Open+Sans:wght@400;600;700&display=swap");

:root {
  --neon-blue: #2563eb;
  --neon-blue-rgb: 37, 99, 235;
  --font-body: "Open Sans", sans-serif;
}
```

### When the designer shares screenshots or describes their brand

This is a common flow: the designer shows what their app looks like and wants the design system to match. Follow this process:

1. **Extract colors** from the screenshots or description. Map them to CSS custom properties in `public/data/design-system/company.css` (NOT `shared.css`):
   - Override `--bg-0`, `--bg-1` for backgrounds
   - Override `--neon-blue`, `--neon-blue-rgb` for the primary accent
   - Override `--neon-teal`, `--neon-teal-rgb` for the secondary accent
   - Add new tokens for any additional brand colors (e.g. `--brand-red`, `--brand-red-rgb`)
   - Override `--text`, `--muted`, `--muted-2` for text hierarchy
2. **Extract typography** -- if they want different fonts, add the `@import` and override `--font-body` and `--font-display` in `company.css`.
3. **Extract spacing and shape** -- override `--radius-*` tokens if their design uses different corner radii. Override `--shadow` and `--shadow-soft` if they use different elevation styles.
4. **Build matching components** using the updated tokens. Each component needs:
   - Preview HTML file in `components/<company-slug>/`
   - Entry in `registry.json`
   - Optionally, CSS classes in `company.css` (prefix with company slug)

### Color component conventions

When creating color palette components for the design system page, render visual swatches so they look good on the design system page.

**Layout — use a grid, not a vertical stack.**

- **Do not** stack swatches in a single column (e.g. one swatch per row). Use a **grid layout** so multiple swatches sit side-by-side and wrap into rows.
- **Preferred:** CSS Grid with a fixed or responsive column count so swatches align in a neat grid:
  - Example: `display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr); gap: 12px;` for a 4-column grid (use 4–6 columns depending on swatch size).
  - Or responsive: `grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(72px, 1fr)); gap: 12px;` so columns adapt to container width.
- **Alternative:** Flexbox with wrap is acceptable: `display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 12px;` — but ensure the container is wide enough that multiple swatches fit per row (do not use a narrow column or `flex-direction: column` for the swatch list).

**Swatch structure (per color):**

- Square (or rounded square) showing the color — e.g. `width` and `height` 48–56px, `border-radius: 10px`, optional thin border for light colors (`border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.1)`).
- Label below: token name and hex (or value), small font (e.g. `font-size: 0.65rem`), muted color.

**Example (grid of swatches):**

```html
<div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(4, 1fr);gap:12px;">
  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;align-items:center;gap:4px;">
    <div style="width:56px;height:56px;border-radius:10px;background:var(--bg-0);border:1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.1);"></div>
    <span style="font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;color:rgba(0,0,0,0.45);"><strong>BG 0</strong> #ffffff</span>
  </div>
  <!-- repeat for each color -->
</div>
```

Group colors logically: backgrounds, accent/brand colors, text colors, semantic colors (success, error, warning).

### Suggested default groups

When building a design system from scratch, use these groups as a starting point (add or rename as needed):

- **Foundations** -- colors, typography, spacing, shadows
- **Inputs & Controls** -- buttons, form fields, toggles, chips, search
- **Feedback & Status** -- badges, tags, alerts, progress, skeleton loaders, toasts
- **Navigation** -- nav bars, tab bars, list items, bottom sheets
- **Cards & Content** -- any domain-specific card types, content rows, media layouts
- **Layout & Structure** -- dividers, avatar groups, section headers

## Tone

> In **core repo mode**, speak technically -- the user is a developer. Skip the simplifications below.

> In **consumer repo mode**, follow these rules:

- Speak simply. Avoid technical terms like "DOM", "component tree", "state management".
- Say "screen" not "page" or "route".
- Say "design system" not "CSS framework".
- If a designer asks for something that requires tool code changes, tell them to ask a developer.
- Be proactive: suggest design system components that fit what they're building.
